🧩 3474. Lexicographically Smallest Generated String

📋 Problem Statement
You are given two strings str1 (length = n) and str2 (length = m).

We need to construct a string word of length n + m - 1 such that:

For every index i:

If str1[i] == 'T'
👉 substring word[i ... i+m-1] == str2
If str1[i] == 'F'
👉 substring word[i ... i+m-1] != str2

🎯 Return the lexicographically smallest valid string.
If impossible → return "".

🧠 Intuition (VERY IMPORTANT 🔥)

💡 Key Observations
T = Strict Constraint
At every 'T', we are forced to place str2 at that position.
These placements may overlap → must match perfectly.
F = Flexible Constraint
At 'F', we just need at least ONE mismatch in that window.
⚠️ Critical Insight

👉 Handle 'T' constraints FIRST
Because they are non-negotiable.

👉 Then fix 'F' constraints
Because they are adjustable.

🔄 Strategy Breakdown
Step 1: Start with smallest string
Initialize word with 'a' everywhere
👉 ensures lexicographically smallest base
Step 2: Apply all 'T' constraints
For each 'T' at index i, force place str2 at i
If overlapping placements conflict → ❌ return ""
Step 3: Handle 'F' constraints
Check if window equals str2
If already different → ✅ good
If same → ❌ must break it
🎯 How to break equality (IMPORTANT)

To keep string lexicographically smallest:

👉 Try modifying rightmost position first

Why?

Changing later characters affects lexicographic order less
🔥 Core Idea
'T' → enforce exact match
'F' → ensure at least one mismatch
Prefer modifying rightmost unlocked position

🧪 Dry Run

Example 1

str1 = "TFTF", str2 = "ab"

Initial word: "aaaaa"

After T placements:

i=0 → "ab___"
i=2 → "__ab_"
Final → "ababa"

Check F:

i=1 → "ba" ≠ "ab" ✅
i=3 → "ba" ≠ "ab" ✅

👉 Answer = "ababa"

Example 2

str1 = "TFTF", str2 = "abc"

Overlapping T placements conflict ❌
👉 return ""

⚡ Optimized Approach

Use:
char[] word
boolean[] locked → marks positions fixed by 'T'

💻 Code (Java)

class Solution {
    public String generateString(String str1, String str2) {
        int n = str1.length(), m = str2.length();
        int len = n + m - 1;
        char[] word = new char[len];
        boolean[] locked = new boolean[len]; // locked by a T constraint
        
        // Fill defaults with 'a'
        java.util.Arrays.fill(word, 'a');
        
        // Step 1: Apply all 'T' constraints
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (str1.charAt(i) == 'T') {
                for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) {
                    int pos = i + j;
                    if (locked[pos] && word[pos] != str2.charAt(j)) {
                        return ""; // conflict
                    }
                    word[pos] = str2.charAt(j);
                    locked[pos] = true;
                }
            }
        }
        
        // Step 2: Handle 'F' constraints
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (str1.charAt(i) == 'F') {
                
                boolean differs = false;
                for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) {
                    if (word[i + j] != str2.charAt(j)) {
                        differs = true;
                        break;
                    }
                }
                
                if (!differs) {
                    boolean changed = false;
                    
                    // Try changing last position first
                    int changePos = i + m - 1;
                    if (!locked[changePos]) {
                        char target = str2.charAt(m - 1);
                        word[changePos] = (target == 'a') ? 'b' : 'a';
                        changed = true;
                    }
                    
                    // Try earlier positions if needed
                    if (!changed) {
                        for (int j = m - 2; j >= 0; j--) {
                            int pos = i + j;
                            if (!locked[pos]) {
                                char target = str2.charAt(j);
                                word[pos] = (target == 'a') ? 'b' : 'a';
                                changed = true;
                                break;
                            }
                        }
                    }
                    
                    if (!changed) return "";
                }
            }
        }
        
        return new String(word);
    }
}

⏱ Complexity Analysis

Type	Complexity
Time	O(n * m) — processing T and F windows
Space	O(n + m) — word + locked array

🔥 Final Takeaway

👉 Think of it as:

Constraint Satisfaction + Greedy Lexicographic Minimization

👉 Order matters:

Lock all 'T'
Fix 'F' minimally

👉 Golden rule:

"Break equality as late as possible to stay lexicographically smallest"